text: I think I first became aware of this when I was working in the back office and I was either working with trade ops or sometimes with ops. There is just an incredible amount of hurting behavior that happens. I don't really necessarily want to know why. I remember when I started, there was the Kramer effect after Mad Money. What is it called? Mad Money. After that show aired, whatever the guy was telling you to buy or telling you to sell, it would move. We've seen it in the Barron's effect. We've seen it in this collective imagination that takes place. I think it's very hard to sit next to somebody that's making money and when you're not making money and you start looking over their shoulder and saying, hey, what are you doing? Maybe you start looking a little bit of that. We saw that a lot of times when conditions lent themselves to uncertainty as to what was going to likely work, people crowded into ideas that somebody else gave them. It was easier. It was easier for people to follow what the sell side was giving you, what the analysts were offering. Obviously, we see these in things like investment fads. We're seeing it right now in the SPAC ecosystem where there's a lot of excitement in it. We saw it earlier this year in these hyper growth companies where the collective imagination really thought of all of these possibilities of this kind of unbounded potential for growth and for profits and for new technologies. People hype. People hype each other up. Then they go online and they talk to each other and they hype each other up even more. You get these crowdings and positioning. One of the things that I've really tried to do is try to see where that kind of fast money is moving. Normally, we think about hedge funds as fast money, but I think lately we have to really consider the individual investor as even faster money. Why? Why do they hold their attentions and their imaginations change awfully quick? One of the ways that we do this is just tracking these narratives and tracking how they manifest themselves in investment instruments, whether that be ... It used to be mutual funds. They're not really worth tracking anymore, especially when you're getting daily data from ETFs and that stuff is really high quality. Yeah.
